{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_katherine_ver01/data/sn89064422/00542865556/1930111401/0587.xml":{"full_text":"\u00bb\\GE FOUR\nEDITORIAL\nEXPRESSIONS\nTHE ORGANIZED FARMER\nMember\ntional Editorial Association\nPublished Every Friday at 524 Plum Street, Red\nWing, Minnesota.\nEntered as second class mail matter at the post\nffice at Red Wing, Minnesota, under the Act of\nMarch 3, 1879.\nSubscription, $2.00 a year, payable in advance.\nAdvertising rates on application.\nMILDRED C. SCHERF PUBLISHER\nF. H. SHOEMAKER EDITOR MANAGER\nPrices paid for milk to farmers is like ev\nerything else, down. If a thoughtful merch\nant would only stop to think, he would vote\nand work, with and for, the very farmer who\nis his best customer. If he could only see that\nthe price of milk in this community has fal\nlen off about SIO,OOO per month or $120,000\nper year, which is some money. Still the av\nerage merchant will work with the very ene\nmies of the farmers who are largely respon\nsible for the condition that robs Red\nWing merchants out SIO,OOO in business ev\nery month.\nThis $120,000 is no longer flowing through\nthe business channels of Red Wing. It is no\nLonger being placed in banks to be reloaned\nto others for the purpose of rebuilding and\nbuilding up this community. Automobiles are\nno longer purchased as they were several\nyears ago, and before the National Chamber\nof Commerce decided to skin the American\nfarmer and worker with the assistance ol\nlocal chambers who are assisting in the steal\nthat is wrecking themselves.\nThe result is that, the farmers are unhap\npy, the workers are hungry, and the, busi\nness men say that \u201cbusiness is rotten.\u201d\nHowever, there are several great corpora\ntions in America who are wallowing in\nwealth, much to the detrement of the farm\ner, worker and little business men. So long\nas the forces of re-action hold sway, and as\nlong as the little merchant insists on biting\nthe hand that feeds him, and listens to the\nrampage that is emitted from the local dai\nlies, there can be no relief.\nIf the business men of Red Wing really\ndid some thinking they would join in with the\nthousands in Goodhue County who have\nseen the light as the last election returns\nshowed, advertise in The Organized Farmer\nand convince the workers and farmers that\nthey are really sincere, it would do a whole\nlot to rebuild a real confidence that would\nassist the entire community and throw\nfear into the forces of re-action that\nare robbing the producers blind, and leav\ning them with no money to spend in the com\nmunity.\nNO WHERE\u2019S \u2018NYE\u2019\nJ. Ham. Lewis, pink parted whiskers and\ndi. was elected to the Senate in Illinois by\n000,000 votes over Ruth Hanna McCormick,\nwho didn\u2019t come anywhere \u2018Nye\u2019 being elec\nted.\nSTARTING ALREADY\nAlreadv Jens K. Grondahl is starting to\nridicule the new Farmer-Labor administra\ntion by nominating Susie W. Stageberg for\nthe position of a member of the Board of\nControl. \u2019Tisn\u2019t funny Jens, both you and Su\nsie need sympathy.\nA new sort of a jagg is taking hold of the\nyoung folks according to the Medical Society.\nThe new jagg consists of aspirin mixed with\nCoca-Cola, the results are said to the same\nas an alcoholic jagg, only some what more\ndangerous. Now for a new organization to\nfight the dreadful COCA COLA.\nPEOPLE REBUKED HIM\nThe manner in which the Old Guard was\neliminated from the Senate does not in any\nway place a vote of confidence for the\n\u2019OOVER administration. They voted dimi\ncratick, which is just as bad if not worse.\nGRATE American peepul sure do know how\nto jump from the frying pan into the fire.\nInstead of voting for principle, they are al\nways voting against somebody.\nA STRONG ARGUMENT\nLiterally, one of the strongest arguments\never offered by a debater won the debate\nfor the Menominee, Michigan high school\nlast Friday night. The debate was on \u201cChain\nStores\u201d.\nThe strong argument against the chains\nwas two pounds of Limberger cheese, one\nought from a chain, and the other from an\n^dependent. The chain store Limberger\nras several ounces short of the standard\n,>ound. This should prove, that in Limberg\n*r there is strength, even in an argument\nthe cheese speaks for itself.\nCUT HIGH COST OF LIVING\nBarney and Roy are doing their bit to as\nsist the poor fellow who is employed at a\nlow salary. They have made a substantial\ncut in the cost of flour as will be seen by the\ndisplay advertisement they have on this\npage.\nAND SO IT IS\nWHAT NEXT\nDEFECTIVE PAGE\nTHE CKeANIgED lAI HII '\u2019u.\nA municipal opera house should be oper\nated for service and not for profit. The re\nverse is true in the city of Red Wing. The\nmanner in which the show business is being\nrun in this city is a crime against the citi\nzens of Red Wing, and especially against\nthe working people of this city, who in the\naggregate pay a large share of the taxes. If\nreports are true, profits of two to four thous\nand dollars per month are made by our mu\nnicipal show house. Profits which are turned\nover into the hands of a so-called board who\nmay spend it as they please. A board that is\nresponsible to no one but themselves, a\nboard that can give out passes galore to those\nwho are most able to pay their way, and a\nboard that would deprive the working man\u2019s\nchild of the opportunity of seeing a show. A\nboard that places the admission price so high\nthat the average working man cannot afford\nto take his children to a show. This is not as\nit should be. This theatre should be operated\nso that the people of Red Wing should be\nprotected against the very things, that they\nare now forced to shoulder. The Organized\nFarmer wants to see this theatre operated\nto give all the people an opportunity of see\ning and enjoying shows, and not for the pur\npose of seeing how much in profits the traf\nfic will bear. One real thing that could be\ndone, and that is to give the children free\nshows on Friday evenings and Saturday af\nternoons. We should at least try to remem\nber the kiddies and be almost human. This\nshould be sufficient to start action along con\nstructive lines.\nWhile there is not much that can be done\nby the poor laboring people to overcome the\nunemployment situation, this, however, can\nbe said, that right here in Red Wing they\nhave at least given the matter attention and\nstudy.\nA committee has been appointed by the\nTrades and Labor Assembly for the purpose\nof working together with any other body of\npublic spirited citizens who feel that the\ncause of the unemployed is worthy. Let us\nhope that every citizen in Red Wing will\ngive serious thought to this great breeder o;\ndiscontent, UNEMPLOYMENT.\nEAT PROHIBITION AND TARIFF\nOnly a superhuman effort by the few org\nanized radicals and humanitarians, and by\nthe masses of organized labor, will bring the\noutgoing Congress, at its session this winter\nto seriously face the emergency created by a\nyear of nationwide unemployment. The na\ntional Capitol, after weeks of revivalist talk\nby the White House, is still fundamentally\nindifferent to the need of 20,000,000 men,\nwomen and children for money with which\nto buy food, clothing, fuel and other neces\nsaries this winter. Local organized charity is\ntrying to raise a few thousands of dollars to\nmeet the November demands, but federal of\nficials are content to read in their daily\nnewspapers that the Hoover-Woods commit\ntees are stirring up the state and municipal\ngovernments, all over the country, to defeat\nunemployment.\u201d How to defeat it they do\nnot venture to inquire.\nIn the reactionary Washington Post ap\npears an editorial which speaks vaguely of\nthe need for greater purchasing power on\nthe people, as an essential to any return of\nprosperity. It suggests that the workers\nmust be able to buy back more of \u201cwhat ;s\nproduced,\u201d so that production can go on. This\napproach toward Marxian economics is not\npermitted to come to any point, however, and\nthe readers of this paper are permitted to re\nturn to their discussions of prohibition and\nthe tariff.\nDIVIDENDS BIGGER THAN EVER\nHunger committees set up by president,\ngovernor and mayor promise to become a ma\njor factor in helping employers to cut the\nAmerican standards of living in confirmitv\nwith the bankers\u2019 ultimatum voiced m the\nnation\u2019s leading financial sheets. The first\nstroke in accustoming befliwered and bera\ndioed American workers to a lower standard\nof living is the recommendation of the Hoov\ner hunger board that workers now on full\ntime be cut to three or four days a week to\ngive employment to the five to eight million\nunemployed. Thus hard times is to be made\na living reality for all workers, whether em\nployed or unemployed.\nWage reductions which will have cut the\nworkers\u2019 share of the national wealth by six\nto 10 billion by next summer are being eng\nineered directly, indirectly and through part\ntime. The direct way, followed in the textile\nand steel industries, among others, is the\n10% cut administered-at varying intervals.\nThe indirect way is that followed by Ford,\nEdison and other ballyhooers of the -high\nwage. They fire their workers and rehire\nthem at a lower scale. Interest and dividend\npayments this year however will be the\ngreatest ever recorded.\nTHE WHOLE PROBLEM SOLVED\nThe opening of a closed factory as a flop\nhouse and the appointment of a governor\u2019s\ncommittee of expert wage cutters to solve\nthe unemployment crisis marked the ack\nnowledgement by Chicago\u2019s prosperity how\nlers that instead of the \u201c12,000 starving\u201d\nthey admitted a week ago there are \u201c300,000\ndestitute\u201d \u2014with worse to come.\nWilliam Wrigley, Jr., who is making more\nthat $1,000,000 a month on chewing gum\nthis year, opened the factory so that 600 men\nmay sleep on the floor. Beds are to be avail\nable soon. HURRAH!\nA NEW FEED INDUSTRY\nIt\u2019s here folks! Yes for some time the far\nmers have prayed that there might be a lit\ntle competition in the feed business. It\u2019s\nhere and you will find an advertisement reg\nularly in this publication.\nIT COULD BE DONE\nDOING THEIR BIT\nPower Trust Gets Jolt\nIn Latest Legal Mixup\nWASHINGTON\u2014(FP)\u2014 Solici\ntor Charles Russell of the Federal\nPower Commission has dealt a\ndeadly blow to the attempt of the\npower trust to evade the provi\nsions of the Federal Power Act\nunder the cloak recently furnished\nthem by Atty. Gen. Mitchell in the\nlatter\u2019s notorious \u201cnon-navigable\nstream\u201d ruling. Mitchell ruled tha;\npower sites at non-navigable\npoints in rivers which are claimed\nfor federal control because they\nare on navigable streams, are ex\nempt from the control provided in\nthe Federal Power Act. Russell,\ndealing with this argument in the\ncase ofthe Columbus (Ga.) Elect\nric Power Co., seeking a power\nsite on the Chattahoochie River,\nproved that the Federal Power\nAct does not apply to all such\ncases.\nNEW YORK (FP) When\nCommunists holding a demonstra\ntion for relief of the unemployed\nir. Brooklyn attempted to mount\nthe municipol building steps in de\nfiance of police orders, 50 police\ncharged, beating them with black\njacks and fists. One girl, Ray Gor\ndon, 18, had several front teeth\nloosened by a blow.\nNEW YORK (FP) 36,833\njobless main supporters of fomilies\nhave been found by police in the\nfive boroughs of New York, rep\nresenting about 150,000 who are\nacutely suffering. Individuals sup\nporting themselves alone are not\ncounted. Relief will not be given\nuntil Nov. 7, after tabulation of\nneeds. The $250,000 monthly relie.\nfund which the mayor was count\ning on from the city employes will\nbe a drop in the bucket according\nto Welfare Comm. Taylor.\nDANVILLE, Va. \u2014(FP)\u2014With\nsupplies from other unions pour\ning in, and the arrival of John W.\nEdelman, research director for the\nFederation of Full Fashioned Hos\niery Workers to help start a drive\nfor funds, the strike of 4,000 tex\ntile workers in Danville entered\nits sixth week. City light was cut\noff in some of the workers\u2019 homes\nfor non-payment of bills, but the\nworkers are using oil and candles.\nThere has been no move for evic\ntions.\nREADING, Pa.\u2014(FP)\u2014With a\nwage cut of over 30% instituted\nby the Berkshire Knitting mills\nformost of its male employes on\nOct. 31, following previous reduc\ntions from 20 to 40% since the\nfirst of the year officials of the\nFederation of Full Fashioned Hos\niery Workers have wired President\nHoover asking him to use his in\nfluence against the step. Hoover\nboasted at the A. F. of L. conven\ntion in Boston that his conference\nwith leaders in industry last Nov\nember have prevented a wage cut\nting campaign. In good times the\nBerkshire firm employes over 8,000\nand the union expects to spread to\nall employes,\nNEW YORK (FP)\u2014 A fine\nTammany gesture for election\npurposes is the 1% assessment lev\nied on all city workers for the em\nergency unemployment fund,\npoints out Pres. Henry R. Lenville\nof the New York Teachers Union.\nBut Tammany\u2019s generosity with\ncity employes\u2019 money does net help\nto solve the unemployment prob\nlem, he declares in a letter to\nPres. George J. Ryan of the school\nboard, protesting certain features\nof the levy. \u201cThe crisis existed last\nwinter,\u201d says Pres. Linville, \u201cand\nneither the federal government nor\nthe City of New York concerned\nthemselves with the situation.\u201d\nWard Miners Lead Strike\nWARD, Va.\u2014(FP)\u2014A strike in\nvolving 800 employes of the Kel\nly\u2019s Creek Colleries Co., threatens\nto spread itself in all the coal\ncamps dotting the West Virginia\nhills of the Kanawha valley.\nThe Ward miners walked out\nseveral weeks ago when represen\ntatives of the coal company posted\nnotices of a wage reduction, bring\ning their wages down, in some in\nstances, to as low as $3 a day.\nSince then committees from other\nED FARMES\nNEWS FROM ALL SECTIONS\nWrecks Girl\u2019s Teeth\nHuge Suffering Found\nAid Danville Strikers\nAsk Hoover\u2019s Aid\n\u201cCampaign All Politics\u201d\nIn substance, Russell shows, by\nnuemerous court decisions, that\nthe regulatory power of Congress\nextends not only to streams which\nare navigable throughout, but to\nstreams which are non-navigable.\nIts control over non-navigable\nstreams \u201cextends to the prohibi\ntion of structures in and upon such\nwaters and to structures in any\nother place or elsewhere undei\nwhich such construction may\nchange their condition.\u201d Sec. 23 of\nthe Federal Water Power Act pro\nvides that whenever construction\nwill affect the interests of inter\nstate or foreign commerce, the ap\nplicant for^a power site cannot\nproceed until it shall receive a li\ncense under the provisions of this\nAct. And these provisions are the\nones that the power companies\nKelly\u2019s Creek mines have visited\nthe strikers bringing word that\nthey were ready to declare war on\nlong hours and starvation wages.\nDenounce British Policy\nWASHINGTON\u2014(FP)\u2014 Reso\nlutions were adopted by the Amer\nican Jewish Congress, in session\nin Washington, denouncing the\n\u201crepudiation of the solemn pledge\ngiven by the British government\nto the Jewish people\u201d involved in\nthe Simpson report on Palestine\npolicy which has been accepted by\nthe London government. This re\nport opposes the importation of\nJewish workers to fill jobs in Pal\nestine when native Arab workers\nwant the jobs. The British govern\nment has declared for suspension\nof immigration to Palestine until\na census shall be taken. The Jew\nish Congress holds this to be a vi\nolation of Britain\u2019s obligation to\nthe League of Nations, assumed\nwhen she received the Palestine\nmandate.\nWomen\u2019s Party Protests\nWASHINGTON \u2014(FP)\u2014 Since\nthe Cotton Textile Institute has,\nafter many years of stubborn op\nposition to the demands of trade\nunions and humanitarians, at last\nagreed to advise cotton mill own\ners to stop employing women and\nchildren in the mills at night, the\nNational Woman\u2019s Party has wir\ned a protest to Walker D. Hines\npresident of the Institute.\nDividends on Increase\nNEW YORK\u2014(FP)\u2014Dividends\ndeclared in October aggregated\nmore than October 1929 due to\npayments in the bank, insurance\nand public utility groups, accord\ning to the New York Times. The\nOctober 1930 total was $310,112,-\n902 compared with $476,094,394 in\nSeptember and $296,791,420 a year\nago.\nLewis Still Scabbing\nSCRANTON, Pa.\u2014(FP)\u2014David\nFowler, directed by John L. Lewis\nto take charge of Indianapolis fac\ntion of the miners union in Ohio,\nstumped the anthracite against\nGifford Pinchot, candidate for gov\nernor of Pennsylvania indorsed by\nthe Pennsylvania Federation of\nLabor.\nWants Soviet Business\nNEW YORK \u2014(FP)\u2014 Because\nthe 11 other directors voted again\nst recognition of Soviet Russia, S.\nStandwood Menken, founder and\nfirst president of the Nat\u2019l Securi\nty League, resigned as head of the\nsuperpatri otic organization. For\nmerly believing communism a\nmenace to this country, he recent\nly stated on his return from a Eur\nopean trip that such an idea was\nabsurd, and that recognition would\nmean a great financial benefit to\nboth countries.\nStrike Ties Texas Ports\nHOUSTON, Tex. \u2014(FP)\u2014 Des\npite asurances of Texas newspa\npers in 1929 that there were no\nindustrial disturbances in Texas\nand that industry instead of going\ntc the southeast could come to\nTexas to avoid labor trouble, 4,000\nlongshoremen, members of the\nInti. Longshoremen\u2019s Assn., on\nOct. 31 tied up shipping in all Tex\nas ports.\nFake Nitro Gets Job\nFORT WORTH, Tex.\u2014 (FP)\nMrs. Mary Rosenthal, 53, was hap\npy when she was locked up in Fort\nWorth\u2019s jail as the result of\nnow seek to evade\u2014requirements\nthat the companies shall not in\nflate in their capitalization the ac\ntual investment made in the dam\nand power plant.\nThis opinion by the solicitor of\nthe Federal Power Commission\nwill be fought by the Electric\nBond Share and other power\ntrust groups, and will be the\ntheme of speeches in Congress\nwhen the confirmation of members\nappointed to the new Power Com\nmission is debated. It gives point\nto Sen. Couzens\u2019 demand for legis\nlation to provide federal regula\ntion of the interstate transmission\nof electric energy, since the power\ntrust has shown that it will resort\nto any slight technicality to avoid\nopening its expense ledger to fed\neral inspection.\nthreatening to blow up the Union\nDank Tiust Co. She demanded\ns 3,000 from the bank\u2019s president,\nbrandishing a bottle which she\nsaid contained nitrogyeerine but\nonly had sweet milk in it.\n\u201cI\u2019m so glad my plan worked,\u201d\nshe said. \u201cI knew he w\u2019ould get\nthe law and that I would get to\nwork for Uncle Sam. I was so glad\nfor I had looked so hard for work.\u201d\nMrs. Rosenthal, with no relatives,\nwas destitute. She begged to be\nsent off to the penitentiary \u201cwhere\nI can work and be taken care of.\u201d\nGALVESTON, Tex. \u2014(FP)-\u2014A\nsoup kitchen has been opened in\nGalveston.\nBARNEY ROY\nI CASH 318 PLUM GROCERY\nFLOUR\nI 98 lb. bag $2.45\nI 49 lb. bag 1.29\nI 24^2 lb. bag 69c\nI Every Bag Guaranteed To Give Utmost Satisfaction\nOr Your Money Cheerfully Refunded\nThe Following Figures Show the Growth of\nLive Stock Commission\nYear\n1926\n1927\n1928\n1929\nGross Sales 1926\nThe above figures show exactly to what extent this organization has expanded\nduring the past four years. Our volume is rapidly growing. Our gains are tre\nmendous. Our service is improving. We are giving our shippers the best the\nmarket will afford. Satisfaction is our watchword. With these mottoes we\nhope to build to a point where the producer will control the market and be able\nto dictate a fair price. The figures show that we have made good to the satis\nfaction of thousands of producers. May we be of service to you in your next\nshipment of live stock? When in So. St. Paul call at our office and w*e shall be\nglad to give you literature.\nLivestock Commission\nNew Route to Slavery\nWEST ORANGE, N. J.\u2014(FP)\n\u2014Thomas A. Edison is a great pal\nof Henry Ford and they both de\nlight in giving expansive stories to\nthe newspaper boys about high\nwages and the great harm of cut\nting pay during a national depres\nsion.\nBut Edison\u2019s plant managers\nsee eye to eye with Ford\u2019s slave\ndrivers in Detroit when it comes\nto reducing costs. Wages are not\ncut\u2014workers arefired and then\nhired at lower wages.\n\u201cAh shuah does pity you,\u201d said\na colored pugilist to his opponent\nas they squared off. \u201cAh was bom\nwith boxing gloves on.\u201d\n\u201cMaybe you was,\u201d retorted the i\nother \u201cand ah reckon you\u2019s goin*'\nBETTER VALUES\nat Your\nIndependent Store\nHe syour friend...the independent merchant. He sells whar loca\nfolks really need, not what some one miles away thinks you ought\nto have.\nThat just naturally points him toward Top Notch Rubbei\nFootwear. Because it is built deliberately to out'\nwear any other ^bber footwear. He knows this,\nbecause his customers tell him so when they come\nback for more.\nWhen you need rubber footwear, swing the\ndoor of your independent store. Say \"Top Notch\u201d\nand get the biggest money\u2019s worth in town.\narctic for all occasions, \u00fcbich wears and looks new\ntor a longer period than you would think an arctic could.\nThe Farmers\u2019 Union\nSouth St. Paul, Minnesota\nCattle\n43650\n43047\n60861\n106364\n1926\n1927\n1928\n1929\nFarmers\u2019 Union\nSouth St. Paul, Minn.\nCHAS. D. EGLEY, Manager\n1\nHogs\n144163\n163171\n196271\n318392\nSheep\n18923\n31269\n57527\n121853\n5195,560.32\n5,003,569.87\n7,261,945.40\n13,168,935.97\nto die de same yray\nSudden Service I\nFeed Grinding j.\nBring in your custom\ngrinding\nOrder seeds and feeds\nnow for future delivery\nJOHNSON\nAND\nARNSON\n211 E. 4th St.\nRail Cars Trucks\n2329 706\n2623 699\n3816 686\n6467 945\nto 1929","height":"28635","width":"21039"}}
